    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Ha74] Hayman, W. K., Research problems in function theory: new problems. (1974), 155--180.",
      "remarks": "This is Problem 4.22 in \\cite{Ha74}, where it is attributed to Erd\\H{o}s. In \\cite{Ha74} it is reported that Clunie and Netanyahu (personal communication) showed that a path always exists which joins $z=0$ to $\\lvert z\\rvert=1$ in $A$.\n\nErd\\H{o}s wrote 'presumably this tends to infinity with $n$, but not too fast'.\n\nThe trivial lower bound for the length of this path is $1$, which is achieved for $f(z)=z^n$. The interesting side of this question is what the worst case behaviour is (as a function of $n$).\n\nSee also [1041]."
    },
